Hi!

Im trying to use DLIB's tools to extract fHoG features from a dataset of .bmp images. I have used the imglab tool provided by DLIB to create the .xml file used in extracting the features, but when I try to open up the file with this call:

`dlib::load_image_dataset(images_train, object_boxes_train, object_directory+"/test.xml");`

I get an image load error. My .xml file is written on this form:

```
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='ISO-8859-1'?>
<?xml-stylesheet type='text/xsl' href='image_metadata_stylesheet.xsl'?>
<dataset>
<name>imglab dataset</name>
<comment>Created by imglab tool.</comment>
<images>
  <image file='positive\pos1.bmp'>
    <box top='926' left='652' width='717' height='301'/>
  </image>
  <image file='positive\pos10.bmp'>
    <box top='858' left='578' width='783' height='344'/>
```

When I tried to debug the error it seems that load_image_dataset thinks that my .xml file is empty. Do you have any ideas as to how I could fix this? I spent a couple of hours marking all the objects, and would rather not have all that time be spent in vain. I am working in Visual Studio 15 on Windows 10. Thanks in advance for any help!

PS: This is the rest of my code for the extraction:

```
void hogFeatureExtraction() {

    String object_directory = "C:/Users/xxxxxx/Documents/Visual Studio 2015/Projects/xxxxxxxx/xxxxxxxx/fhog_feature_extraction";

    dlib::array<dlib::array2d<unsigned char>> images_train;

    std::vector<std::vector<dlib::rectangle>> object_boxes_train;

    dlib::load_image_dataset(images_train, object_boxes_train, object_directory+"/test.xml");

    typedef dlib::scan_fhog_pyramid<dlib::pyramid_down<6>> image_scanner_type;

    image_scanner_type scanner;

    scanner.set_detection_window_size(75, 30);

    dlib::structural_object_detection_trainer<image_scanner_type> trainer(scanner);

    trainer.set_num_threads(4);

    trainer.set_c(1);

    trainer.be_verbose();

    trainer.set_epsilon(0.01);

    dlib::object_detector<image_scanner_type> detector = trainer.train(images_train, object_boxes_train);

    dlib::image_window hogwin(draw_fhog(detector), "Learned fHOG detector");

}
```

PPS: I also submitted this issue on StackOverflow, and I will close both of the posts as soon as I solve this issue :)

